      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The straight-line depreciation formula is simply: (Cost - Salvage Value) / Useful Life. So, for your machine, you take the $50,000 cost, subtract the $5,000 salvage value to get $45,000, and divide that by the 5 years to get $9,000 per year.\n\nHowever, I must remind you that accounting is not just about numbers; it's about the *cost* of the asset. If you buy a machine for $50,000, you are essentially paying $50,000 to the machine, but you are also paying $5,000 to the scrap value you'll get when it's gone. The difference is what you actually spend on the machine over its life.\n\nThink of it this way: you pay the full $50,000 upfront, but you get to \"sell\" the machine for $5,000 at the end. So, the net cost to you is $45,000. Over 5 years, that's $9,000 a year.\n\nNow, here is where the *actual*",
